# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1796-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The **Twelfth Amendment** (**Amendment XII**) to the United States Constitution provides the procedure for electing the president and vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] It replaced the procedure in Article II, Section 1, Clause 3, under which the Electoral College originally functioned.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The amendment was proposed by Congress on December 9, 1803, and was ratified by the requisite three-quarters of state legislatures on June 15, 1804.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The new rules took effect for the 1804 presidential election and have governed all subsequent presidential elections.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Initially under the Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two electoral votes, with no distinction between electoral votes for president or for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The presidential candidate receiving the greatest number of votes—provided that number was at least a majority of the electors—was elected president, while the presidential candidate receiving the second-most votes was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In cases where no individual won the votes of a majority of the electors, as well as in cases where multiple persons won the votes of a majority but tied for the most votes, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In cases where multiple candidates tied for the second-most votes, the Senate would hold a contingent election to select the vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The first four presidential elections were conducted under these rules.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The original system allowed the 1796 and 1800 presidential elections to elect a president and vice-president who were political opponents, constantly acting at cross-purposes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This was the case as John Adams (Federalist) had to deal with Thomas Jefferson (Democratic Republican) as his vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] There was also the danger of two or more candidates tying in the electoral college.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This was the case in 1800 when Jefferson and Aaron Burr, though both Anti-Federalist, were indeed tied in the college.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This spurred legislators to amend the presidential election process to require each member of the Electoral College to cast one electoral vote for president and one electoral vote for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Under the original procedure for the Electoral College, as provided in Article II, Section 1, Clause 3, each elector cast two electoral votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The two people chosen by the elector could not both inhabit the same state as that elector.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This prohibition was designed to keep electors from voting for two "favorite sons" of their respective states.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The person receiving the greatest number of votes, provided that number constituted a majority of the electors, was elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] There were two possible scenarios in which the House of Representatives would need to hold a contingent election to select the president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] If there were more than one individual who received the same number of votes, and such number equaled a majority of the electors, the House would choose one of them to be president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] If no individual had a majority, then the House would choose from the five individuals with the greatest number of electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In both sets of circumstances, each state delegation had one (en bloc) vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] A candidate was required to receive an absolute majority, more than half of the total number of states, in order to be chosen as president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Selecting the vice president was a simpler process.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Whichever candidate received the second greatest number of votes for president became vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The vice president, unlike the president, was not required to receive votes from a majority of the electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In the event of a tie for second place, the Senate would hold a contingent election to select the vice president from those tied, with each senator casting one vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] A candidate was required to receive an absolute majority, more than half of the total Senate membership, in order to be chosen as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The original electoral system worked adequately for the first two presidential elections because on both occasions George Washington was the unanimous choice of the electors for president; the only real contest was the election for vice president for which an overall majority was not required.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] George Washington's decision not to seek a third term and the emergence of partisan political activity exposed problems with the original procedure.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In the 1796 election, John Adams, the Federalist Party presidential candidate, received votes from a majority of electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, the Federalist electors scattered their second votes, resulting in the Democratic–Republican Party presidential candidate, Thomas Jefferson, receiving the second highest number of electoral votes and thus being elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] It soon became apparent that having a vice president and a president unwilling to work together effectively was going to be a more significant problem than was originally realized.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The most significant problem was that with the French Revolutionary Wars raging in Europe, it was immediately apparent that President Adams was going to pursue a pro-British foreign policy, much to the disgust of the strongly pro-French Vice President Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] On January 6, 1797, Federalist Representative William L.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Smith of South Carolina responded to the 1796 result by presenting a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution requiring each elector to cast one vote for president and another for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, no action was taken on his proposal.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In the 1800 election, both major parties attempted to prevent the problem that arose in 1796 by nominating separate presidential and vice presidential candidates on a party ticket.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, there was no way for the electors to distinguish between the two offices when they cast their votes, so if all the electors voted for their party tickets, the election would end in a tie between the two candidates from the most popular ticket.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Democratic-Republicans, who had nominated Jefferson for president and Aaron Burr for vice president, managed to secure a majority of pledged electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] But the electoral margin was so slim that there was little room for error if the Democratic–Republicans were to avoid repeating the Federalists' miscues of 1796.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Given the technical limitations of 18th-century communications, Democratic–Republican electors in each state were left to assume that an elector in some other state was the one responsible for casting the one abstention necessary to ensure the election of Burr to the vice presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In the event, all the Democratic–Republicans electors were so reluctant to be responsible for causing outgoing President Adams to be elected as vice president that every Democratic–Republican elector cast a vote for both Jefferson and Burr, resulting in a tie.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This problem was termed later the Burr dilemma.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Consequently, a contingent presidential election was held in the House of Representatives.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Federalist-controlled state delegations cast their votes for Burr in an effort to prevent Jefferson from becoming president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] With help from Alexander Hamilton, the gridlock was finally broken on the 36th ballot and Jefferson was elected president on February 17, 1801.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This prolonged contingent election, combined with the increasing Democratic–Republican majorities in both the House and the Senate, set the stage for a constitutional amendment to alter this flawed system.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In March 1801, weeks after the election of 1800 was resolved, two amendments were proposed in the New York State Legislature that would form the skeleton of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Governor John Jay submitted an amendment to the state legislature that would require a district election of electors in each state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Assemblyman Jedediah Peck submitted an amendment to adopt designations for the votes for president and vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The two amendments were not considered until early 1802 because the state legislature took a break for the summer and winter.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] New York state senator DeWitt Clinton moved for the adoption of the amendment in January 1802.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Shortly thereafter, Clinton won a vacant seat in the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Senate, where he was instrumental in bringing the designation amendment to Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The process continued in New York on February 15 when Representative Benjamin Walker of New York proposed the designation and district election amendments to the House.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Democratic-Republicans wanted to decide on the amendment quickly, but the Federalists argued that the ideas needed more time than the current session allowed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Dana of Connecticut wanted to examine the necessity of a vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The amendment ultimately failed in the New York State Senate, but DeWitt Clinton brought the amendment discussion to the House of Representatives.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Congress was ready to debate the presented amendment, but the Democratic–Republicans decided to wait for the 8th Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The 8th Congress would allow the Democratic–Republicans a better chance of meeting the two-thirds vote requirement for submitting a proposed Constitutional amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In 1803, on its first day, the 8th Congress considered the designation amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The first formulation of the amendment had the five highest electoral vote earners on the ballot in the House if no one candidate had a majority of the electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Democratic–Republican John Clopton of Virginia, the largest state in the Union, argued that having five names on the list for a contingency election took the power from the people, so he proposed that there be only two names on the list.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] On October 20, the House appointed a seventeen-member committee (one Representative from each state) to fine-tune the amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The original proposal starting in the New York State Legislature would have, along with designation, put forward the idea of the district election of electors that Treasury Secretary Gallatin had supported.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Shortly after the committee was formed, Federalist Benjamin Huger attempted to add a provision regarding district elections to the proposed amendment, but the committee ignored him.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The committee then submitted an updated version of the designation amendment to the House on October 23 that changed the number of candidates in a contingency election from five to three and allowed the Senate to choose the vice president if there were a tie in that race.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Small Federalist states disliked the change from five to three because it made it far less likely that a small-state candidate would make it to a contingency election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Huger and New York Federalist Gaylord Griswold argued that the Constitution was a compromise between large and small states and the method chosen by the Framers is supposed to check the influence of the larger states.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Huger even asserted that the Constitution itself was not a union of people, but a union of large and small states in order to justify the original framework for electing the president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Designation, argued Griswold and Huger, would violate the spirit of the Constitution by taking away a check on the power of the large states.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Next up for the Federalists was Seth Hastings of Massachusetts, who submitted the argument that the designation amendment rendered the vice presidency useless and advocated the elimination of the three-fifths clause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Smith asked the inflammatory question of whether the proposed amendment was to help Jefferson get reelected.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Speaker Nathaniel Macon called this inappropriate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Matthew Lyon of Kentucky denounced any reference to the three-fifths clause as mere provocation.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The House proceeded to pass the resolution 88–31 on October 28, 1803.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Many Northern representatives argued for the elimination of the electoral college, and argued for direct election of the President by all U.S. voters.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] By October 28, the Senate had already been discussing the designation amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Democratic–Republican DeWitt Clinton expected that the Senate, with a 24–9 Democratic–Republican majority would quickly pass the amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Federalist Jonathan Dayton proposed that the office of the vice president should be eliminated and his colleague, Uriah Tracy, seconded it.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] On the other side, Wilson Cary Nicholas was simply worried that Congress would not submit the amendment in time for the states to ratify it before the 1804 election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Despite Nicholas' concern, the Senate would not seriously deal with the amendment again until November 23.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Much as it had in the House, debate centered on the number of candidates in a contingency election and the philosophical underpinnings of the Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Again, small Federalist states vehemently argued that three candidates gave too much power to large states to pick presidents.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina argued that the issues with the election of 1800 were unlikely to happen again and he would not advocate changing the Constitution simply to stop a Federalist vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] John Quincy Adams argued that the change from five to three gave an advantage to the people that violated the federative principle of the Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Rather than have the office of the president balanced between the states and the people, Adams felt designation of president and vice president would tip that scale in favor of the people.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Federalist senators argued for retaining the original procedure for the Electoral College.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Senator Samuel White of Delaware claimed that the original procedure had not been given "a fair experiment" and criticized the proposed amendment for entrenching the two-party system which had taken over presidential elections.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In response, the Democratic–Republicans appealed to democratic principles.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Samuel Smith of Maryland argued that the presidency ought to be as closely accountable to the people as possible.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] As such, having three candidates in a contingency election is far better than having five, because it would otherwise be possible to have the fifth best candidate become president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Also, designation itself would drastically cut down the number of elections that would reach the House of Representatives, and the president is then much more likely to be the people's choice.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Another of Smith's arguments was simply the election of 1800.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] William Cocke of Tennessee took a different approach when he argued that the entire small state argument of the Federalists was simply out of self-interest.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] One last order of business for the amendment was to deal with the possibility that the House would fail to choose a president by March 4.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] It was the least controversial portion of the Twelfth Amendment and John Taylor proposed that the vice president would take over as president in that peculiar occurrence, "as in case of the death or other Constitutional disability of the President".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] It seemed clear all along that the Democratic–Republican dominance would render this a no-contest and the Democratic–Republicans were just waiting for all their votes to be present, but the Federalists had one last defense.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] A marathon session of debate from 11:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m. was the order of the day on December 2, 1803.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Most notably, Uriah Tracy of Connecticut argued in a similar vein as Adams when he invoked the federative principle of the Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Tracy claimed the original procedure was formulated to give the small states a chance to elect the vice president, who would be a check on the president's powers.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In essence, the states balanced the power of the people.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, this works only if you make it partisan, as Georgia (for example) was a Democratic–Republican small state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment was proposed by the 8th Congress on December 9, 1803, when it was approved by the House of Representatives by vote of 84–42, having been previously passed by the Senate, 22–10, on December 2.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] New Hampshire: June 15, 1804 Having been ratified by the legislatures of three-fourths of the several states (13 of 17), the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment was completed and it became a part of the Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The amendment was rejected by Delaware, on January 18, 1804, and by Connecticut, on May 10, 1804.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In a September 25, 1804, circular letter to the governors of the states, Secretary of State James Madison declared the amendment ratified by three-fourths of the states.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] While the Twelfth Amendment did not change the composition of the Electoral College, it did change the process whereby a president and a vice president are elected.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The new electoral process was first used for the 1804 election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Each presidential election since has been conducted under the terms of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment stipulates that each elector must cast distinct votes for president and vice president, instead of two votes for president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The upshot of this rule is that presidential candidates have refrained from selecting a running mate who lives in the same state that they do, lest they risk losing either the presidential or vice presidential votes from electors from their shared home state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] For instance, at the beginning of 2000, Dick Cheney and George W.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Bush were both legally residents of Texas; but, in preparation for being nominated as Bush's running mate, Cheney changed his legal residence to Wyoming, where he owned a home and which he had previously represented in Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] If no candidate for president has a majority of the total votes, the House of Representatives, voting by states and with the same quorum requirements as under the original procedure, chooses the president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This is the only proceeding in which the House votes by state delegation.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment requires the House to choose from the three highest receivers of electoral votes, compared to five under the original procedure.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment requires a person to receive a majority of the electoral votes for vice president for that person to be elected vice president by the Electoral College.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] If no candidate for vice president has a majority of the total votes, the Senate, with each senator having one vote, chooses the vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment requires the Senate to choose between the candidates with the "two highest numbers" of electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] If multiple individuals are tied for second place, the Senate may consider them all.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment introduced a quorum requirement of two-thirds of the whole number of senators for the conduct of balloting.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Furthermore, the Twelfth Amendment requires the Senate to choose a vice president by way of the affirmative votes of "a majority of the whole number" of senators.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Twelfth Amendment did not state for how long the vice president would act as president or if the House could still choose a president after March 4.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] It also clarifies that if there is no president-elect on January 20, whoever acts as president does so until a person "qualified" to occupy the presidency is elected to be president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Some contend that the Twelfth Amendment concerns qualification for *service*, while the Twenty-second Amendment concerns qualifications for *election*, and thus a former two-term president is still eligible to *serve* as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Some legal scholars propose the contention above would inadequately consider the opportunity it affords for one to serve as president more than two terms plus "[acting] as President, for more than two years," resulting in a violation of the Twenty-second Amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The interaction between the two amendments has not been tested, as no twice-elected president has ever been nominated for the vice presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, in striking down term limits imposed by state governments on members of Congress in *U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Thornton* (1995), the Supreme Court held that term limits amount to a qualification for holding public office referencing the 22nd Amendment, stating that "the Nation as a whole... has imposed a limit on the number of terms that the President may serve.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Hillary Clinton jokingly said during her 2016 presidential campaign that she had considered naming her husband, twice-elected former president Bill Clinton as her vice presidential running mate, but had been advised it would be unconstitutional.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] This constitutional ambiguity allowed for speculation in 2020 about whether twice-elected former president Barack Obama was eligible to be vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Starting with the election of 1804, each presidential election has been conducted under the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] As the House could consider only the top three candidates, Clay was eliminated, while Crawford's poor health following a paralytic stroke made his election by the House unlikely.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Jackson expected the House to vote for him, as he had won a plurality of both the popular and electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Instead, the House elected Adams on the first ballot with thirteen states, followed by Jackson with seven and Crawford with four.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Clay had endorsed Adams for the presidency, which carried additional weight because Clay was the Speaker of the House.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Adams subsequently appointed Clay as his Secretary of State, to which Jackson and his supporters responded by accusing the pair of making a "corrupt bargain".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In the election for vice president, John C.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Calhoun (the running mate of both Jackson and Adams) was elected outright, receiving 182 electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In 1836, the Whig Party nominated four different candidates in different regions, aiming to splinter the electoral vote while denying Democratic nominee Martin Van Buren an electoral majority and forcing a contingent election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Ultimately Van Buren won the electoral college outright and the attempt to invoke the 12th Amendment proved fruitless.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The Whig strategy narrowly failed as Van Buren won an electoral vote majority and an apparent popular vote majority, winning Pennsylvania by 4,222 votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In South Carolina, whose presidential electors were Whigs, no popular vote was held as the state legislature chose the electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] The basis for the Whigs' strategy lay in a severe state-level Democratic Party split in Pennsylvania that propelled the Whig-aligned Anti-Masonic Party to statewide power.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Party alignments by state in the House of Representatives suggest that any contingent election would have had an uncertain outcome, with none of the candidates (Van Buren, William Henry Harrison and Hugh White) having a clear path to victory.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In that same election, no candidate for vice president secured an electoral majority as the Democratic electors from Virginia refused to vote for Democratic vice presidential nominee, Richard Mentor Johnson, due to his relationship with a former slave, and instead cast their votes for William Smith.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] As a result, Johnson received 147 electoral votes, one vote short of a majority, followed by Francis Granger with 77, John Tyler with 47 and Smith with 23.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Thus, it became necessary for the Senate to hold a contingent election between Johnson and Granger for vice president, which Johnson won on the first ballot with 33 votes to Granger's 16.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Since 1836, no major U.S. party has nominated multiple regional presidential or vice presidential candidates in an election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, since the Civil War, there have been two serious attempts by Southern-based parties to run regional candidates in hopes of denying either of the two major party tickets an electoral college majority.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Both attempts (in 1948 and 1968) narrowly failed; in both cases, a shift in the result of two or three close states would have forced these respective elections into the House (for president) and Senate (for vice president).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] In modern elections, a running mate is often selected in order to appeal to a different set of voters.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] A Habitation Clause issue arose during the 2000 presidential election contested by George W.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Bush (running-mate Dick Cheney, who Bush selected) and Al Gore (running-mate Joe Lieberman), because it was alleged that Bush and Cheney were both inhabitants of Texas and that the Texas electors therefore violated the Twelfth Amendment in casting their ballots for both.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Texas' 32 electoral votes were necessary in order to secure Bush and Cheney a majority in the Electoral College.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Bush's residency was unquestioned, as he was Governor of Texas at the time.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] However, Cheney and his wife had moved to Dallas five years earlier when he assumed the role of chief executive at Halliburton.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Cheney had grown up in Wyoming, had represented it in Congress and had continuously maintained a residence in the state during his tenure at Halliburton.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] A few months before the election, he switched his voter registration and driver's license to Wyoming and put his home in Dallas up for sale.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] On July 21, 2000, Cheney changed his voter registration from Texas to Teton County, Wyoming.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/12th-amendment-to-the-u-s-constitution] Three Texas voters challenged the election in a federal court in Dallas and then appealed the decision to the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, where it was dismissed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Portions of dialogue and some lyrics were taken directly from the letters and memoirs of the actual participants of the Second Continental Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Adams, representing Massachusetts in the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, laments the body's refusal to debate his motion to declare the colonies' independence from Great Britain and instead to discuss more trivial matters.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Disliked by most of his fellow Congressmen, he frequently seeks advice and comfort from his wife, Abigail.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania, one of the few who enjoys Adams' company due mainly to their shared dream of independence, suggests someone else propose the independence resolution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Richard Henry Lee of Virginia eagerly agrees, and he rides home to get authorization from the state legislature to do so.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Lee returns, proposes the resolution and, over the objections of John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, leader of the Conservative faction seeking reconciliation with Britain, Congress agrees to debate the question, which becomes heated as tempers flare.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Caesar Rodney of Delaware, suffering from cancer, collapses and is forced to leave during the debate, depriving Adams of Delaware's vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A new delegation from New Jersey arrives and votes in favor of independence (Franklin receives word that his son William, the Royal Governor of New Jersey, has been arrested).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Seeking to kill the motion, Dickinson successfully moves that an independence vote be unanimous on the grounds that "no colony be torn away from its mother country without its own consent." To salvage the motion, Adams asks for a postponement to draft a declaration of grievances.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] President of the Congress, John Hancock, breaks the tie vote in favor of a declaration and appoints Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Thomas Jefferson of Virginia to a committee to write it.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite his determination to go home to his wife, Martha, Jefferson reluctantly agrees to be the primary writer.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After a full week passes without Jefferson's being able to complete the task, Adams summons Martha to Philadelphia; Martha charms both Adams and Franklin, and Jefferson finishes the draft.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] To convince Samuel Chase of Maryland to support independence, Adams agrees to accept General George Washington's plea to visit the army encampment in New Brunswick, New Jersey, taking Franklin and Chase with him.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After the members return to their lodgings, a young military courier arrives and sadly relates to Congressional custodian Andrew McNair how his two best friends were killed in battle at Lexington.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After Adams and Franklin return from New Jersey, the Declaration is read to the full Congress, which begins accepting many amendments.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Jefferson agrees to almost all of the changes, except striking language referring to King George as a "tyrant" and objecting to slavery.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina leads the Southern members in walking out in protest just as Chase returns with Maryland's vote supporting independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Frustrated at Adams's refusal to compromise, Franklin tells him that to achieve the primary goal of independence Adams must accept that those with opinions contrary to his will be part of their new nation.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Badly shaken, Adams again seeks counsel from Abigail, and thanks to a delivery of much-needed saltpeter from her and the delegate from Georgia's sudden decision to support independence, Adams finds the strength and will to continue.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On the day of the vote (July 2, 1776), Adams and Jefferson agree to drop the slavery provision, and Rutledge and the other Southern states vote for independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] With Delaware divided, Rodney is brought back to support independence by majority vote of its three representatives.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Eventually, all states vote for independence except divided Pennsylvania and New York, whose remaining representative, Lewis Morris, has abstained throughout the proceedings.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] When Dickinson rises to vote against the proposal, Franklin moves that the Pennsylvania delegation be polled: he votes for independence and Dickinson votes against it, leaving the question up to James Wilson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Not wanting to be remembered for casting the decisive vote against American independence, Wilson votes in favor.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Dickinson resigns from Congress and vows to join the army to support the fight against the British, even though he believes it to be futile.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] As the members prepare to sign the Declaration of Independence on July 4, 1776, Morris receives word that his estates have been destroyed and his family moved to safety.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite not being authorized, Morris signs anyway.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] As McNair tolls the building's bell, one member per state signs, establishing the United States of America.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] An asterisk (*) indicates an actor or actress who was also in the original Broadway cast.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] An original motion picture soundtrack album was released in 1972 by Columbia Records on vinyl LP records.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It contains all the musical numbers, with the exception of "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" and "Compliments".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The soundtrack also contains the edited versions of some of the musical numbers that were presented in full on the laserdisc and DVD releases.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Although the Original Broadway Cast recording was released on CD in 1992, the film soundtrack remains unavailable in any digital format as of 2026.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner bought the film rights to the musical for $1.25 million.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Many members of the original Broadway cast, including William Daniels, Ken Howard, John Cullum, and Howard da Silva, reprised their roles for the film.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Ralston Hill, Ron Holgate, David Ford, Charles Rule and others repeated their roles from the Broadway production, marking their only appearances in feature film.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This was a decision Warner made himself after feeling he made a mistake by turning down Julie Andrews for the 1964 film adaptation of *My Fair Lady* in favor of Audrey Hepburn.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Exteriors were filmed at the Warner Ranch in Burbank, California, the former Columbia Pictures backlot, where they built an entire street of Colonial Philadelphia.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Most of the Colonial sets were destroyed by a fire in the mid-1970s.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The water fountain seen during the musical number "The Lees of Old Virginia", with Ben Franklin, John Adams, and Richard Henry Lee, became known to television viewers as the fountain seen during the beginning credits of the TV series *Friends*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This fountain still exists directly across the street from the *Bewitched* and *I Dream of Jeannie* houses.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Interiors were shot at the old Columbia studio on Gower Street in Hollywood.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] *1776* was among the final films shot at Gower Studios before the Warner/Columbia merger in 1971.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men" was cut from the film prior to its release and not included on the soundtrack recording nor on the first VHS tapes and laserdiscs.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The *Los Angeles Times* stated "The song 'Cool, Cool, Considerate Men' depicts Revolutionary War–era conservatives as power-hungry wheedlers focused on maintaining wealth." According to Jack L.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner, the film's producer and a friend of President Richard Nixon, Nixon requested the song be removed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner's attempt to comply with Nixon's demands had initially been rebuffed by director Hunt during production, only for the song to be removed in post-production while Hunt was on vacation.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner also wanted the original negative of the song shredded, but the film's editor kept it in storage unaltered.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (The footage, some of physically poor quality, was restored for the DVD and Blu-Ray releases.) Trailers had already been released in theaters with the "Considerate Men" number as its centerpiece; Warner had those trailers pulled and re-edited.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In a 2015 interview, Hunt mentioned that Warner, on his deathbed in 1978, told a friend that he regretted editing the scene, believing he had ruined the film's structure as a result.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It was only decades later that the song was restored to the film.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] When the Broadway musical was about to be presented to Nixon at the White House in 1970, before the film was made, his staff pressed the producers to cut the song then; their request was denied.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Some of the dialogue was taken from words written, often years or even decades later, by the actual people involved, and rearranged for dramatic effect.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film particularly omits the views of the mid-Atlantic Quaker population, represented by Dickinson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A supposed physical fight between Dickinson and Adams is portrayed, in which Dickinson calls Adams a "lawyer" as an epithet, despite the fact that Dickinson was a lawyer himself.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite the film's inclusion of Martha Jefferson and Abigail Adams, Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris Dickinson, was the only spouse actually present in Philadelphia during the convention.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, had died a year or so earlier.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Another departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The wording of the Declaration of Independence—the statement to the world as to the reasons necessitating the split—was then debated for three days before being approved on July 4.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The vote for independence did not hinge on passages being removed from the Declaration, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] For the sake of drama, the play's authors combined the two events.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In addition, some historians believe the Declaration was not signed on July 4, but on August 2, 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Others note that the final copy of the document was signed by the delegates over several weeks and months, commencing in July and not completed until as late as September.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Liberty Bell in *1776* is shown being rung as the delegates were signing the Declaration on July 4; however, Independence Hall's wooden steeple was structurally unstable, and the Liberty Bell was silent, having been lowered into the upper chamber of the brick tower.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A smaller bell, used to toll the hours, may have rung on July 8, for the public reading of the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Many characters in *1776* differ from their historical counterparts.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Central to the drama is the depiction of John Adams as "obnoxious and disliked." According to biographer David McCullough, Adams was one of the most respected members of Congress in 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams's often-quoted description of himself in Congress as "obnoxious, suspected, and unpopular" is from a letter written 46 years later in 1822, after his unpopular presidency had likely colored his view of the past.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] According to McCullough, no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Historian Garry Wills earlier made a similar argument, writing that "historians relay John Adams's memories without sufficient skepticism", and that it was Dickinson, not Adams, who was advocating an unpopular position in 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Committee of Five appointed to write the Declaration of Independence were: Franklin, age 70 (Howard da Silva was 62 at the time of filming in 1971); Roger Sherman, 55 (Rex Robbins was 36); Adams, 41 (Daniels was 44); Jefferson, 33 (Ken Howard was 27); and Livingston, 29 (John Myhers was 49).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams" say Livingston claims to have "been presented with a new son by the noble stork" to avoid writing the declaration; no such son ever existed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] For practical and dramatic purposes, only 20 of the over 50 members of Congress present at the time are portrayed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This version of John Adams is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who was in Congress at the time but is mentioned as being absent in the script.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Although the play depicts Delaware's Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 years old at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles (130 km) the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter) unaided, instead of with the help of another delegate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Further, Richard Henry Lee announces that he is returning to Virginia to serve as governor.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was never governor (it was Lee's ally Patrick Henry who assumed the post at that time); his cousin Henry Lee (who is anachronistically called "General 'Lighthorse' Harry Lee", a rank and nickname earned later) did eventually become governor (and the father of Confederate general Robert E.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Adams was also depicted as disliking Richard Henry Lee, but according to McCullough, Adams expressed nothing but "respect and admiration for the tall, masterly Virginian." He did dislike Benjamin Franklin, contrary to what was portrayed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband; she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The play's authors invented the scene "to show something of the young Jefferson's life without destroying the unity of setting." Martha is also depicted as dancing a galop or polka with Franklin and Adams, dances not introduced until the 1800s.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The real Martha Jefferson would have been seated playing the early piano Thomas purchased for her, accompanying him as he played violin.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film, like its stage counterpart, misidentifies John Morton, the deciding vote and a soft-spoken judge who only votes for the resolution to avoid being infamous for killing it, as James Wilson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The real Wilson, though he had previously studied under Dickinson earlier in his career, had by 1776 become one of the most outspoken advocates for independence, and would only later become a judge on the Supreme Court.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] His patrician WASP accent in the film is misleading, since Wilson was a Scottish immigrant whose parents were farmers, while Morton's family was from Finland.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The quote attributed to Edmund Burke by Dr.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Lyman Hall in a key scene with Adams is a paraphrase of a real quote by Burke.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic; the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Dickinson, who is portrayed as an antagonist here, was motivated mainly by his Quaker roots and his respect for the British Constitution, having lived in England for 3 years in the 1750s.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was no wealthier than some members of the pro-Independence faction, and freed his slaves in 1777.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Thomas Jefferson wrote that "his name will be consecrated in history as one of the great worthies of the revolution".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film also misses the objection some had to the Declaration's stated basis in "rights of Man" based in "natural law" derived from a supernatural being.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Quaker-based population in the mid-Atlantic, represented by Dickinson, objected to this conception.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical also deviates from history in its portrayal of attitudes about slavery.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In *1776*, after a dramatic debate over slavery, the southern delegates walk out in protest of the Declaration's denunciation of the slave trade, and only support independence when that language was removed from the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The walkout is fictional, as the debate over the wording of the declaration took place after the vote for independence on July 2, and apparently most delegates, northern and southern, supported the deletion of the clause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical depicts Edward Rutledge as the leader of the opposition to an anti-slavery clause in Jefferson's original draft of the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] However, while it is known that, according to Jefferson, the clause was opposed by South Carolina and Georgia, plus unspecified "northern brethren", that is all that is known about opposition to the clause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Rutledge was a delegate from South Carolina, but there is no historical evidence that he played any part—much less a leadership role—in the opposition to the clause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical does acknowledge the complexity of the Colonial attitudes toward slavery in the dramatic song "Molasses to Rum," sung by the Rutledge character, which illustrates the hypocrisy in northern condemnations of slavery since northerners profited from the triangle trade.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical depicts Franklin as claiming that he is the founder of the first abolitionist organization in the New World; the real Franklin did not become an abolitionist until after the American Revolution, becoming president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society in 1785.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It was actually Dickinson who freed his slaves in 1776, conditionally at first, and fully by 1787 when the Constitution was ratified.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In both the play and the film, John Adams sarcastically predicts that Benjamin Franklin will receive from posterity too great a share of credit for the Revolution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] "Franklin smote the ground and out sprang—George Washington.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] James Wilson is portrayed as subordinating himself to Dickinson's opposition to independence, only changing his vote so that he would not be remembered unfavorably.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In fact, Wilson was considered one of the leading thinkers behind the American cause, consistently supporting and arguing for independence, although he would not cast his vote until his district had been caucused.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The formula John Adams gives Abigail for making saltpeter—"By treating sodium nitrate with potassium chloride, of course!"—refers to various chemicals by their modern names, instead of the names used in the 1770s.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A more historically accurate version might be "treating soda niter with potash." More accurate still would have been a detailed description of the process, involving ingredients such as manure or bat guano, but that probably would have been too long, and repulsive to audiences.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Abigail's request for pins in exchange is not frivolous.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Electroplating had not been invented yet: The common pin was subject to rusting and breakage, and so required replacement.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] At the time, pins were necessary for a wide range of crafts, creating garments and headgear (including wigs), making lace, ribbon and other trimmings and textiles.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] They also served the roles now played by paperclips and staples.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Women used them as closures or to anchor pieces of clothing.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (Hooks and eyes existed, but like so many manufactured goods, they had to be imported.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The hook-and-eye industry was not established in the United States until the early 19th century.) The real Abigail, if dressed as in this scene in the film, would have supported the front lacing of her gown by using pins to fasten the fabric to the stiffened bodice beneath.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Vincent Canby of *The New York Times* observed, "The music is resolutely unmemorable.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The lyrics sound as if they'd been written by someone high on root beer, and the book is familiar history—compressed here, stretched there—that has been gagged up and paced to Broadway's not-inspiring standards.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Hunt's screen version of *1776* ... insists on being so entertaining and, at times, even moving, that you might as well stop resisting it.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I've seen *1776* now four times and it may well be that the repetition has worn grey my true-blue patriotism.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The movie is a good technical copy but rather than adding to the original in any meaningful way it merely fills it out with the usual superfluity of second-hand screen work.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Peter Hunt has directed with a view to maximum expenditure of energy.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] There is absolutely no chance that anyone will go to sleep during *1776*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Most of the actors were brought to the film from the hugely successful stage version and they all know how to milk a scene for full value." Carole Kass of the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* stated that "the film, even though the conclusion is historical knowledge, is still suspenseful.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] One cares very much about the individual delegates and their votes, opting from the theater seat for freedom.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film is also a reminder that when it came to pitting the status quo against progress, Virginia was one of the first to vote for tomorrow.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In Philadelphia, the film opened to significantly different reactions across two of its daily newspapers.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Collins of *The Philadelphia Inquirer* called the film "an affront because it trivializes a big subject without any redeeming satirical intent.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Founding Fathers are not cut down to human size, they are reduced to subhuman dimensions.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] They are made into singing clowns whose boobish behavior somehow produces one of the most eloquent expressions of the human spirit ever to come from the hand of man." On the other hand, Joe Baltake of the *Philadelphia Daily News* called it "a pompous, roguish, disarmingly charming movie musical.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Its original freshness is retained largely because its 1969 Broadway ancestor never attained the household-word popularity of, say, *My Fair Lady* and *The Sound of Music*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Its storyline still comes across as something delightfully novel, as does its spirited score.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Unlike other stage-to-screen adaptations, this 'new' entertainment is free of the usual telltale staleness. [...] Under director Peter Hunt's guidance, the off-beat material works surprisingly well in musical form.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A heavy hand could have been disastrous.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In fact, even with Hunt's light touch, "1776" occasionally gives way to a sluggish stuffiness.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Some forbearance is necessary for total enjoyment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Sherman Edwards' unusual songs remain the work's high point, especially "The Egg," "He Plays His Violin," "Sit Down, John" and the haunting "Momma, Look Sharp." Technically, the film is visually enchanting—a giant kaleidoscope of sprawling sets, period costumes and gobs of color.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The production design is equalled only by the admirable ensemble acting.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film got similarly mixed reviews in Chicago.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Roger Ebert of the *Chicago Sun-Times* gave *1776* two stars and declared, "This is an insult to the real men who were Adams, Jefferson, Franklin and the rest ...
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The performances trapped inside these roles, as you might expect, are fairly dreadful.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] There are good actors in the movie (especially William Daniels as Adams and Donald Madden as John Dickinson), but they're forced to strut and posture so much that you wonder if they ever scratched or spit or anything ...
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I can hardly bear to remember the songs, much less discuss them.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The movie received generally positive reviews in the United Kingdom.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Alexander Walker of the *Evening Standard* said "it ought to be heavy going and yet the surprising thing is I didn't find it so.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The energy is infectious." He also stated that "since it was written Into the record, *1776* could hardly ignore the moment when the reference to the slave trade was shamefully, but conveniently, struck out of the Declaration of Independence in order to carry the vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams—a fine role for William Daniels." It was not without its detractors in England, however.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I only wish I could say this fidelity to the original concept actually worked, but the fact is you have to keep pinching yourself to remember that you're watching movie.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 68% score, based on 19 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was the Christmas attraction at Radio City Music Hall in New York City and performed very well, grossing $1,743,978 in its first six weeks.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It did not perform as well in its other opening engagements in Philadelphia, Boston and Washington.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It returned to the Music Hall for two weeks starting June 3, 1976 in honor of the United States Bicentennial.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy but lost to *Cabaret*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Harry Stradling Jr. was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Cinematography but lost to Geoffrey Unsworth for *Cabaret*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was first released on videocassette, which runs 148 minutes, and on Laserdisc in the 1980s.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Laserdisc version runs 180 minutes and is rated PG.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The DVD, issued in 2002 as a "Restored Director's Cut", runs 165 minutes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It trims up some scenes and contains previously unreleased scenes, including the "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" musical number and accompanying dialogue.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] However, it excludes the previously released Overture (heard on laserdisc but not in cinemas).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was released on Blu-ray from a 4K-master on June 2, 2015.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It contains two commentaries: an all-new commentary, with director Hunt, Daniels and Howard, and also the DVD commentary with Hunt and Peter Stone only.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] With two versions: the prior "Director's Cut", and a further "extended cut" (167 minutes), the release also includes two deleted and alternative scenes with filmmaker commentary, screen tests, and original theatrical trailers.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On May 31, 2022, Sony Pictures released a three-disc 50th anniversary Blu-ray.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1972, it was made into a film adaptation, with eight of the original Broadway actors reprising their roles.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] It has received three New York revivals: on Broadway in 1997, an Encores! concert in 2016, and a 2022 Broadway production in which the racially diverse cast was entirely made up of people who identify as female, trans, or non-binary.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1925, Rodgers and Hart wrote a Broadway musical about the American Revolution called *Dearest Enemy*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1950, another musical about the Revolution was presented on Broadway, titled *Arms and the Girl*, with music by Morton Gould, lyrics by Dorothy Fields, and book by Herbert Fields, Dorothy Fields and Rouben Mamoulian, the show's director.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Sherman Edwards, a jazz pianist and Brill Building pop songwriter who had decades prior had minor roles in Broadway musicals, began developing lyrics and libretto for a musical based on the signing of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Edwards recounted that "I wanted to show [the founding fathers] at their outermost limits.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] These men were the cream of their colonies. ...
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] They disagreed and fought with each other.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The first songs in the project were published and copyrighted by 1964.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Producer Stuart Ostrow recommended that librettist Peter Stone collaborate with Edwards on the book of the musical.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, the outspoken delegate from Massachusetts, was chosen as the central character, and his quest to persuade all 13 colonies to vote for independence became the central conflict.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone confined nearly all of the action to Independence Hall and the debate among the delegates, and featuring two female characters, Abigail Adams and Martha Jefferson, in the musical.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] After tryouts in New Haven, Conn., and Washington, D.C., the show opened on Broadway at the 46th Street Theatre on March 16, 1969.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On May 8, 1776, the Second Continental Congress, convening in Philadelphia at present-day Independence Hall, proceeds with its business.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] John Adams, the controversial delegate from Braintree, Massachusetts, is frustrated because Congress will not even debate his proposals on independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Later, Adams meets delegate Benjamin Franklin, an elderly lecherous scamp, who suggests that Adams should let another, more popular delegate propose a resolution on independence and summons the charismatic Richard Henry Lee of Stratford, Virginia.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Lee eagerly agrees to return to Virginia to procure an independence resolution from the Virginia House of Burgesses using his family's reputation and clout ("The Lees of Old Virginia").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As Congress is assembled, President John Hancock notes that the entire New Jersey delegation has been absent for quite some time.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A gloomy dispatch from George Washington, commander of the Continental Army, arrives by courier and is read aloud by Secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Shortly thereafter, Richard Henry Lee returns, bearing a resolution for independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Elated, Adams seconds the motion to open debate on the resolution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, a conservative and royal apologist, immediately moves to table the debate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote is close, but debate is ultimately approved, prompting Dickinson to denounce the desire for independence as an overreaction to petty squabbles with Great Britain.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The debate becomes more heated and personal, sparking a physical fight between Dickinson and Adams and causing Caesar Rodney to intervene; Rodney collapses from cancer.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Pro-independence Scotsman Thomas McKean escorts Rodney back to Delaware, leaving conservative George Read in control of Delaware's delegation.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Read quickly seconds Rutledge's motion to end the debate and vote on independence, knowing it is likely to fail.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] At this moment, the Reverend John Witherspoon arrives, announcing that New Jersey's legislature has deposed its royal governor, Franklin's estranged loyalist son, and has sent Witherspoon as the new delegate with explicit instruction to vote for independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, now seeing a path to victory, pushes to proceed with the vote, since ties are broken by Hancock, an Adams ally who is also from Massachusetts.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson moves to require the vote for independence to be unanimous.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote ends in a tie, but Hancock unexpectedly votes in favor of unanimity, explaining that if the colonies are divided, the crown will pit the colonies against each other.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Knowing that Dickinson will quash the resolution if the vote proceeds immediately, Adams moves to postpone the vote to buy time to rally the needed support; he proposes that Congress draft a Declaration of Independence to build support abroad for the cause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Again, the vote ties; this time, Hancock votes to postpone.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Before they adjourn, John Hancock appoints a committee of Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Lee to draft the declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Lee informs the Congress that he has been appointed Governor of Virginia and departs, never to be seen again; Adams nominates another Virginian, the resident meteorologist Thomas Jefferson, who wants no part of the task as he is returning home to see his wife after six months.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Jefferson is forced to accept the task after the other four explain why they cannot or should not ("But, Mr.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams sends for Jefferson's beloved wife Martha, reasoning that if Thomas cannot return to her, she can be summoned to him and potentially break his writer's block.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] When she arrives, she refuses to speak to Adams or Franklin and spends the night with her husband.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, alone, again exchanges letters with his wife Abigail ("Yours, Yours, Yours").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The next morning, Franklin and Adams again attempt to engage Martha in conversation; she speaks, but tersely, and talks of her courtship with Thomas ("He Plays the Violin").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams is delighted to find that Jefferson has written something, but instead of work on the declaration, it is a mere note asking for him and Martha to be left alone.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In June, with the Congress in what looks like a state of total lethargy, another grim dispatch from General Washington arrives, denouncing the Continental Army recruits as useless, undisciplined and outmatched, having fallen prey to numerous prostitutes at the camp in New Brunswick, New Jersey.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, sensing that Washington is exaggerating the crisis in hopes of securing more money, convinces Samuel Chase of Maryland to go with him to New Brunswick to test Chase's fears that the Revolutionary War is doomed to end in defeat; Franklin, eager to see the prostitutes for himself, tags along.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The conservatives depart, leaving McNair, the courier (a Continental Army corporal from Watertown, Massachusetts), and a teenage "leather apron" (workman) alone in the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As McNair begins a mock session as *president pro tempore*, he escorts the courier to Adams's seat; there, the courier and McNair discourage the leather apron from joining the Army as the courier recalls his friends' deaths at Lexington ("Momma Look Sharp").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As Congress reconvenes in Philadelphia, Jefferson is outside the chamber while Thomson reads the completed draft of the declaration to the Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams and Franklin arrive, delighted: though the troops are indeed undisciplined, they showed exceptional shooting skill hunting waterfowl for dinner, and this convinced Chase to vote for independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] They congratulate Jefferson on his work, and Franklin compares the creation of this new country to the hatching of a bird, though they disagree on what kind ("The Egg").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On June 28, Hancock asks if there are any alterations to be offered to the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many delegates voice suggestions, additions or deletions.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina objects in particular to a clause condemning the slave trade.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Rutledge leads a walk-out with the delegates from both Carolinas and Georgia, and the rest of the Congress follows.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, who insists on including the slavery clause on principle that excluding it would make the Congress hypocrites, discusses the matter with Franklin, who tells Adams that he must accept some degree of compromise if he wants the independence resolution to pass.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams calls on Abigail in his mind to help him, and she reminds him of his commitment to the cause ("Compliments").
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Bolstered by her (and the arrival of a delivery of kegs of saltpeter he had previously requested from her), Adams recovers his energy and sends Franklin to try and win the support of Pennsylvania's James Wilson and Jefferson to talk to Rutledge.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Re-reading a dispatch from Washington, Adams, now alone, wonders "Is Anybody There?" Hall returns; after considering the words of Edmund Burke, he decides to buck his constituency's loyalist preference and use his own judgment to vote Yea for independence on Georgia's behalf.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hancock calls for the vote on the Lee Resolution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] At this moment, Rodney returns to Congress to assure that Delaware will vote in favor of independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Although Pennsylvania passes on their first call, the rest of the New England and Mid-Atlantic colonies vote in favor of independence except for New York, who reluctantly abstains.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] South Carolina, North Carolina and Georgia all vote "yea".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On Pennsylvania's second call, Dickinson is about to announce that his colony votes "nay" when Franklin requests that the delegation be polled.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hancock proposes that no man be allowed to sit in Congress without signing the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson resigns but pledges his loyalty to the new nation and says he will join the army and fight on its behalf, even as he hopes for eventual reconciliation with England.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams leads the Congress in a salute to Dickinson as he leaves the chamber.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The courier arrives with another dispatch from General Washington; on the eve of the British army's looming attack on New York, Washington remarks on the bravery of his outmatched band of misfit militia members.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Washington also notes that Lewis Morris's family estate has been completely destroyed but that the Morris family was rescued and his sons joined the Continental Army.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Morris, in response, announces "To hell with New York" and agrees to sign the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On July 4, McNair is sent to ring the Liberty Bell.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] It is heard ringing in the background as Thomson calls one delegate from each colony to sign the Declaration, establishing the United States of America.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The delegates freeze in position as the Liberty Bell rings to a fevered pitch.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] After out-of-town tryouts, the original Broadway production opened on Broadway on March 16, 1969, at the 46th Street Theatre (now the Richard Rodgers Theatre) and closed on February 13, 1972, after 1,217 performances.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In its three-year run, it played in three different theatres: the 46th Street, the St.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] James Theatre (1970) and, finally, the Majestic Theatre (1971).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The principal cast included William Daniels, Howard da Silva, Paul Hecht, Clifford David, Ronald Holgate, David Ford, Virginia Vestoff and Ken Howard.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Rex Everhart, who was da Silva's understudy, replaced him on the original Broadway cast album after da Silva suffered a mild heart attack, which required him to leave the show temporarily.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Betty Buckley made her Broadway debut as Martha Jefferson in the original stage production.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Clifford David left the production soon after opening.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] He was replaced as Rutledge by David Cryer who was in turn replaced by John Cullum who became one of the few Broadway replacements in history to recreate a role on film.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical toured for two years in the United States and was given a London production, opening on June 16, 1970, at the New Theatre.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The production starred Lewis Fiander as Adams, Vivienne Ross as Abigail Adams, Ronald Radd, Bernard Lloyd, David Kernan as Rutledge, John Quentin as Jefferson and Cheryl Kennedy as Martha Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] An Australian production, also with Lewis Fiander, opened at Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne on 26 June 1971 and moved to the Theatre Royal in Sydney on 11 September 1971.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] City Center staged concert from March 30 to April 3, 2016.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast included MacIntyre Dixon, Ric Stoneback, and Kevin Ligon reprising their roles from the 1997 revival as Andrew McNair, Samuel Chase, and George Read respectively.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The production notably sported a racially diverse cast in light of the recent success of another musical about the Founding Fathers, *Hamilton*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical was produced in Chicago, Illinois by Porchlight Music Theatre as part of their "Porchlight Revisits" series in November 2018.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Directed by Michael Weber, Music Directed by Jeremy Ramey, with Musical Staging by Michelle Lauto.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The team held a two-week workshop on Zoom in April 2020, but the production was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In June 2021, A.R.T. announced that the production, now directed by Jeffrey L.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Page and Paulus, would begin performances at A.R.T. in May 2022.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast (many of whom were making their Broadway debuts) included Crystal Lucas-Perry (later Kristolyn Lloyd) as Adams, Patrena Murray as Franklin, Elizabeth A.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Davis as Jefferson, Allison Kaye Daniel as Abigail/Rev.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hall, Carolee Carmello as Dickinson and Sara Porkalob as Rutledge.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A two-part radio production adapted and directed by Martin Jarvis starring Alfred Molina as Benjamin Franklin, Ioan Gruffud as John Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical was performed in April 2026 at the Paper Mill Playhouse in Millburn, New Jersey under the direction of Mark S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hoebee with musical staging by Nancy Renée Braun.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast starred Will Blum as John Adams, Michael Burrell as Thomas Jefferson, and John Treacy Egan as Benjamin Franklin.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In the 2022 revival, the end of Act I is moved to after "He Plays the Violin".
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] According to Peter Stone, Scene Three of *1776* holds the record for the longest time in a musical without a single note of music played or sung —– over thirty minutes pass between "The Lees of Old Virginia" and "But Mr.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On the DVD commentary, Stone says that he experimented with adding various songs in this section, but nothing ever worked.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] During this scene, dubbed "Big Three" by cast members, musicians were allowed to leave the pit, reportedly the first time in Broadway history that they were permitted to do so in the middle of a show.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone also notes that people often told him that, because of the subject matter and the large amount of dialogue, *1776* should have been a conventional play rather than a musical.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone believes that the songs create a playful, irreverent tone that helps bring the historical characters to life.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The central departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote for independence did not hinge on some passages being removed from the Declaration, as implied in the play, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence before debating the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In addition, some historians believe that the Declaration was not signed on July 4, as shown in *1776*, but was instead signed on August 2, 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The authors of *1776* had the delegates sign the Declaration on July 4 for dramatic reasons.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The pro-slavery and anti-black views espoused by Rutledge in the play bear similarities to his record, though Rutledge had supported the Lee Resolution and led the campaign to convince the other South Carolina delegates to support it.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Of the four principal characters, the musical also notably focuses on Jefferson's wife, Martha, and Adams' wife, Abigail, but omits Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris, who was actually in Philadelphia, unlike the other wives, and was an active correspondent with the other Founding Fathers.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, was deceased at this point.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams's memories near the end of his life were, according to McCullough, likely distorted and affected by his troubled tenure as President in the late 1790s; no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] For practical and dramatic purposes, the play depicts only 19 of the more than 50 members of Congress who were present at the time.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The John Adams of the play is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who is noted in the play as being absent.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Although the play depicts Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Richard Henry Lee did not leave Congress to serve as Governor of Virginia, a post assumed at the time by Patrick Henry.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In real life, he and his brother Francis were present to sign the Declaration, and his cousin "Light-Horse Harry" Lee, mentioned in "The Lees of Old Virginia" as a general, had only reached the rank of captain by 1776.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams had more admiration for the "tall, masterly Virginian" Lee than the play initially implies.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In fact, she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Jefferson rushed his work on the Declaration so he could return to Martha as soon as he could, and did so no later than August 1776, nine months before the birth of their short-lived son.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic, not only because of its quotation of the not-yet-written "The Star-Spangled Banner," but because the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson, who refused to sign the Declaration based on "rights of man" and "natural law", was seeking to avoid reopening issues from the English Civil Wars, including Oliver Cromwell's Puritan regime, and the Jacobitism cause.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1689, these issues had been definitively resolved in the Glorious Revolution and the constitutionalization of the English Bill of Rights based in "rights and responsibilities of person"; the word "man" is not used except in the context of treason.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The last Jacobite rebellion, seeking to re-establish Catholicism and the religious concept of "natural law", had only just happened in 1745, however.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] None of this background of Dickinson's position is depicted.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Joseph Hewes is portrayed as having little to contribute to the debates, only to consistently yield to, and vote with, Rutledge.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] According to Adams's recollections several decades later, Hewes in fact was staunchly against independence but eventually and reluctantly conceded to popular support once reconciliation appeared to be impossible.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Thomas Jefferson is depicted as saying that he has resolved to free his slaves, something he did not do, except for a few slaves freed after his death 50 years later, due to the massive debt his estate incurred and the need to keep them on the books as collateral.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many of Jefferson's slaves, particularly the Hemings family, were related by blood to Martha (and, after Martha's death, Jefferson is believed to have fathered others); he fought to keep the family united and treated them with privileges rare for slaves of the era.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin claims that he is the founder of an abolitionist organization (the Pennsylvania Abolition Society); however, he had only joined said society in 1785, nine years after the declaration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical misidentifies John Morton, the soft-spoken, experienced judge who cast the deciding vote in favor of independence solely to avoid the infamy of being the single vote that vetoed it, as James Wilson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Wilson had been cautious about supporting independence at an earlier date, but he supported the resolution of independence when it came up for a vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Wilson was in fact one of the most outspoken political leaders of his era, as records tied to the later Constitutional Convention show, and would only become a judge after said Constitution was adopted.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The desire to not singlehandedly block the independence resolution was a joint decision of all the Pennsylvania delegates; in real life, Dickinson and another delegate agreed not to attend the July 2 vote to allow Franklin, Wilson and Morton to vote yes on Pennsylvania's behalf.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The phrase "We are about to brave the storm in a skiff made of paper", placed in the mouth of John Hancock, was actually stated by John Dickinson ("Others strenuously assert...we ought to brave the Storm in a Skiff made of Paper.") in his arguments against independence.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin's comments about the eagle and the turkey in "The Egg" were based on comments he had made in a 1784 letter he had written criticizing the Society of the Cincinnati for, among other perceived wrongs, using an eagle as a symbol.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Furthermore, it was not Adams who chose the eagle as the *de facto* national bird, but instead secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The 2022 revival production includes an excerpt of Abigail Adams' March 1776 letter to John Adams, known for its "remember the ladies" statement for women's rights.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The 1972 film version of *1776* was produced by Jack L.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Warner with Hunt again directing and Stone writing the screenplay.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The film featured William Daniels as Adams, Ken Howard as Jefferson, Howard da Silva as Franklin, John Cullum as Edward Rutledge, Ron Holgate as Richard Henry Lee, and Virginia Vestoff as Abigail Adams, all of whom had performed their roles on Broadway.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The supporting cast was also mostly recruited from the Broadway production.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The principal exceptions were Donald Madden and Blythe Danner, who took over the roles of John Dickinson and Martha Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A Director's Cut of the original film has been released on DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Both the look and sound of the original film have been improved through modern technology.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many cuts to the original film by the producer Jack Warner have been restored, including verses from the songs "Piddle Twiddle and Resolve" and "He Plays the Violin" and the entire "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men,” which Warner originally cut at the urging of President Nixon.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Nixon felt the scene presented conservatism in a negative light.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Musical underscoring has been removed from several scenes without songs in order to strengthen the focus on dialogue.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Bonus material includes commentary by Director Peter Hunt and by Peter Stone, the book/screenwriter.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Among other topics, they discuss artistic liberties and anachronisms used to dramatize the events.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical *Hamilton* references the song "Sit Down, John!" in a lyric from the song, "The Adams Administration", in the lyric: "Sit down, John, you fat mother—[BLEEP]er." Lin-Manuel Miranda discovered the *1776* film in college and cites it as having paved the way for *Hamilton*.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] A presidential election was held in South Carolina on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1789 United States presidential election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose 7 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina, which became the 8th state on May 23, 1788, unanimously cast its seven electoral votes for George Washington during its first presidential election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1796-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
